# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ninja-build
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ninja-build/build-automation] Build automation encompasses both sequencing build operations via non-interactive interface tools and running builds on a shared server.
[src:ninja-build/build-automation] Build automation tools allow sequencing the tasks of building software via a non-interactive interface.
[src:ninja-build/build-automation] A *build system* or *build automation tool* is a programming tool or set of tools that automate the compiling and linking of source code into an executable program or library.
[src:ninja-build/build-automation] They streamline the software development process by managing dependencies, resolving conflicts, and ensuring consistent builds across different environments.
[src:ninja-build/build-automation] When software projects grow complex, their build steps may involve multiple programming languages or compiling units, making manual build processes increasingly cumbersome.
[src:ninja-build/build-automation] Dependencies between code components necessitate careful ordering and potentially different tools for each piece.
[src:ninja-build/build-automation] Managing these dependencies manually can quickly lead to version conflicts, stale binaries, and difficulty tracking updates, making solutions such as shell scripts too difficult to maintain.
[src:ninja-build/build-automation] While individual developers might compile code directly, a robust build system is foundational to efficient software development in large organizations and teams, where automated builds become commonplace and most builds are triggered automatically rather than manually.
[src:ninja-build/build-automation] Given the essential role of build systems, it is said that they act as "repositories of essential build knowledge".
[src:ninja-build/build-automation] They effectively eliminate roadblocks and accelerate development velocity by enabling engineers to share resources and results.
[src:ninja-build/build-automation] An incremental build is a process within a build system where build tools use an incremental compiler to recompile only the parts of a software project that have changed since the last build, rather than rebuilding everything from scratch.
[src:ninja-build/build-automation] This optimization reduces build time by leveraging dependency tracking, caching, and selective compilation.
[src:ninja-build/build-automation] Incremental builds are especially valuable in large-scale software projects, where recompiling the entire codebase can be time-consuming and resource-intensive.
[src:ninja-build/build-automation] By identifying and compiling only the modified components—such as source files, libraries, or modules—the build system ensures faster iteration cycles, enabling developers to test and debug changes more efficiently.
[src:ninja-build/build-automation] The process relies on a dependency graph, which maps relationships between files, modules, or components in the project.
[src:ninja-build/build-automation] When a change is detected, the build system traverses this graph to determine which parts of the project are affected and need to be recompiled.
[src:ninja-build/build-automation] Modern build tools, such as Make, Gradle and Bazel, often incorporate incremental build capabilities to streamline development workflows.
[src:ninja-build/build-automation] While incremental builds offer significant performance advantages, they also introduce challenges, such as ensuring the accuracy of dependency tracking and avoiding stale or inconsistent build artifacts.
[src:ninja-build/build-automation] To address these issues, some build systems provide mechanisms for "clean builds," which rebuild the entire project from scratch to guarantee correctness when necessary.
[src:ninja-build/build-automation] Because of this issue, incremental builds are rarely used in continuous integration systems, where correctness is preferred to compilation speed.
[src:ninja-build/build-automation] Tools such as Make can be used via custom configuration file or using the command-line.
[src:ninja-build/build-automation] Custom tools such as shell scripts can also be used, although they become increasingly cumbersome as the codebase grows more complex.
[src:ninja-build/build-automation] Some tools, such as shell scripts, are task-oriented declarative programming.
[src:ninja-build/build-automation] They encode sequences of commands to perform with usually minimal conditional logic.
[src:ninja-build/build-automation] Some tools, such as Make are product-oriented.
[src:ninja-build/build-automation] They build a product, a.k.a. target, based on configured dependencies.
[src:ninja-build/build-automation] A build server is a server setup to run builds.
[src:ninja-build/build-automation] In contrast to a personal computer, a server allows for a more consistent and available build environment.
[src:ninja-build/build-automation] Traditionally, a build server was a local computer dedicated as a shared resource instead of used as a personal computer.
[src:ninja-build/build-automation] Today, there are many cloud computing, software as a service (SaaS) websites for building.
[src:ninja-build/build-automation] A continuous integration server is a build server that is setup to build in a relatively frequent way, often on each code commit.
[src:ninja-build/build-automation] A build server may also be incorporated into a tool for application release automation (ARA) or application lifecycle management (ALM).
[src:ninja-build/build-automation] Automating the build process is a required step for implementing continuous integration and continuous delivery (CI/CD), all of which are considered best practices for software development.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] In software development, **Make** is a command-line interface software tool that performs actions ordered by configured dependencies as defined in a configuration file called a *makefile*.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] It is commonly used for build automation to build executable code (such as a program or library) from source code.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] Make is also not limited to building and can perform any operation available via the operating system shell.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] Make is widely used, especially in Unix and Unix-like operating systems, even though many competing technologies and tools are available, including similar tools that perform actions based on dependencies, some compilers and interactively via an integrated development environment.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] In addition to referring to the original Unix tool, Make is also a technology since multiple tools have been implemented with roughly the same functionality – including similar makefile syntax and semantics.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] Stuart Feldman created Make while at Bell Labs.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] An early version was completed in April 1976.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] Feldman received the 2003 ACM Software System Award for authoring Make.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] — Stuart Feldman, *The Art of Unix Programming*, Eric S.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] Before Make, building on Unix mostly consisted of shell scripts written for each program's codebase.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] Make's dependency ordering and out-of-date checking makes the build process more robust and more efficient.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] The makefile allowed for better organization of build logic and often fewer build files.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] Make is widely used in part due to its early inclusion in Unix, starting with PWB/UNIX 1.0, which featured a variety of software development tools.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] Make has been implemented numerous times, generally using the same makefile format and providing the same features, but some providing enhancements from the original.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] POSIX includes standardization of the basic features and operation of the Make utility, and is implemented with varying degrees of compatibility with Unix-based versions of Make.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] In general, simple makefiles may be used between various versions of Make with reasonable success.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] GNU Make, Makepp and some versions of BSD Make default to looking first for files named "GNUmakefile", "Makeppfile" and "BSDmakefile" respectively, which allows one to put makefiles which use implementation-defined behavior in separate locations.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] In general, based on a makefile, Make updates target files from source files if any source file has a newer timestamp than the target file or the target file does not exist.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] For example, this could include compiling C files (`*.c`) into object files, then linking the object files into an executable program.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] Or this could include compiling TypeScript files (`*.ts`) to JavaScript for use in a browser.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] Other examples include: convert a source image file to another format, copy a file to a content management system, and send e-mail about build status.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] A makefile defines targets where each is either a file to generate or is a user-defined concept, called a *phony* target.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] If no target is specified, Make updates the first target in the makefile which is often a phony target to perform the most commonly used action.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] Make skips build actions if the target file timestamp is after that of the source files.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] Also, if a source file's timestamp is in the future, make repeatedly triggers unnecessary actions, causing longer build time.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] When Make starts, it uses the makefile specified on the command-line or if not specified, then uses the one found by via specific search rules.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] Generally, Make defaults to using the file in the working directory named Makefile.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] GNU Make searches for the first file matching: GNUmakefile, makefile, or Makefile.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] Make processes the options of the command-line based on the loaded makefile.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] The **makefile** language is partially declarative programming where end conditions are described but the order in which actions are to be taken is not.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] Each rule begins with a *dependency line* which consists of the rule's target name followed by a colon (:), and optionally a list of targets (also known as prerequisites) on which the rule's target depends.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] Usually a rule has a single target, rather than multiple.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] A dependency line may be followed by a recipe: a series of TAB indented command lines that define how to generate the target from the components (i.e. source files).
[src:ninja-build/make-software] If any prerequisite has a more recent timestamp than the target file or the target does not exist as a file, the recipe is performed.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] Each command line must begin with a tab character.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] Even though a space is also whitespace, Make requires tab.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] Since this often leads to confusion and mistakes, this aspect of makefile syntax is subject to criticism.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] Raymond describes it as "one of the worst design botches in the history of Unix" and *The Unix-Haters Handbook* said "using tabs as part of the syntax is like one of those pungee [sic] stick traps in *The Green Berets*".
[src:ninja-build/make-software] Each command is executed in a separate shell.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] Since operating systems use different shells, this can lead to unportable makefiles.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] For example, GNU Make (all POSIX Makes) executes commands with /bin/sh by default, where Unix commands like cp are normally used.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] In contrast, Microsoft's *nmake* executes commands with cmd.exe where batch commands like copy are available but not necessarily cp.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] The following example rule is evaluated when Make updates target file.txt via `make file.txt`.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] If file.html is newer than file.txt or file.txt does not exist, then the command is run to generate file.txt from file.html.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] Ignoring errors and silencing echo can alternatively be obtained via the special targets `.IGNORE` and `.SILENT`.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] Microsoft's NMAKE has predefined rules that can be omitted from these makefiles, e.g.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] Macros are usually referred to as *variables* when they hold simple string definitions, like `CC=clang`.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] Macros in makefiles may be overridden in the command-line arguments passed to the Make utility.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] Environment variables are also available as macros.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] For example, the macro `CC` is frequently used in makefiles to refer to the location of a C compiler.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] If used consistently throughout the makefile, then the compiler used can be changed by changing the value of the macro rather than changing each rule command that invokes the compiler.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] A macro value can consist of other macro values.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] The value of macro is expanded on each use lazily.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] A macro is used by expanding either via $*NAME* or $(*NAME*).
[src:ninja-build/make-software] The latter is safer since omitting the parentheses leads to Make interpreting the next letter after the `$` as the entire variable name.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] An equivalent form uses curly braces rather than parentheses, i.e.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] Macros can be composed of shell commands by using the command substitution operator `!=`.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] Makefiles can access predefined *internal macros*, with `?` and `@` being common.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] A common syntax when defining macros, which works on BSD and GNU Make, is to use +=, ?=, and != instead of the equal sign (=).
[src:ninja-build/make-software] Suffix rules have "targets" with names in the form `.FROM.TO` and are used to launch actions based on file extension.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] In the command lines of suffix rules, POSIX specifies that the internal macro `$<` refers to the first prerequisite and `$@` refers to the target.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] Suffix rules cannot have any prerequisites of their own.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] If they have any, they are treated as normal files with unusual names, not as suffix rules.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] GNU Make supports suffix rules for compatibility with old makefiles but otherwise encourages usage of *pattern rules*.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] A pattern rule looks like an ordinary rule, except that its target contains exactly one `%` character within the string.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] The target is considered a pattern for matching file names: the `%` can match any substring of zero or more characters, while other characters match only themselves.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] The prerequisites likewise use `%` to show how their names relate to the target name.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] Single-line comments are started with the hash symbol (#).
[src:ninja-build/make-software] A directive specifies special behavior such as including another makefile.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] Line continuation is indicated with a backslash `\` character at the end of a line.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] The following commands are in the context of the makefile that follows.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] Below is a simple makefile that by default (the "all" rule is listed first) compiles a source file called "helloworld.c" using the system's C compiler and also provides a "clean" target to remove the generated files if the user desires to start over.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] The `$@` and `$<` are two of the so-called internal macros (also known as automatic variables) and stand for the target name and "implicit" source, respectively.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] In the example below, `$^` expands to a space delimited list of the prerequisites.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] There are a number of other internal macros.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] Many systems come with predefined Make rules and macros to specify common tasks such as compilation based on file suffix.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] This lets users omit the actual (often unportable) instructions of how to generate the target from the source(s).
[src:ninja-build/make-software] That "helloworld.o" depends on "helloworld.c" is now automatically handled by Make.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] In such a simple example as the one illustrated here this hardly matters, but the real power of suffix rules becomes evident when the number of source files in a software project starts to grow.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] One only has to write a rule for the linking step and declare the object files as prerequisites.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] Make will then implicitly determine how to make all the object files and look for changes in all the source files.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] Simple suffix rules work well as long as the source files do not depend on each other and on other files such as header files.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] Another route to simplify the build process is to use so-called pattern matching rules that can be combined with compiler-assisted dependency generation.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] As a final example requiring the gcc compiler and GNU Make, here is a generic makefile that compiles all C files in a folder to the corresponding object files and then links them to the final executable.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] Before compilation takes place, dependencies are gathered in makefile-friendly format into a hidden file ".depend" that is then included to the makefile.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] Portable programs ought to avoid constructs used below.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] Makefile consist of dependencies and a forgotten or an extra one may not be immediately obvious to the user and may result in subtle bugs in the generated software that are hard to catch.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] Various approaches may be used to avoid this problem and keep dependencies in source and makefiles in sync.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] One approach is using the compiler to keep track of dependencies changes.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] GCC can statically analyze the source code and produce rules for the given file automatically by using the `-MM` switch.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] The other approach would be makefiles or third-party tools that would generate makefiles with dependencies (e.g.
[src:ninja-build/make-software] Automake toolchain by the GNU Project, can do so automatically).
[src:ninja-build/make-software] Another approach is to use meta-build tools like CMake, Meson etc.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] It takes as input the interdependencies of files (typically source code and output executables) and orchestrates building them, *quickly*.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Ninja joins a sea of other build systems.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] It is born from my work on the Chromium browser project, which has over 30,000 source files and whose other build systems (including one built from custom non-recursive Makefiles) would take ten seconds to start building after changing one file.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Where other build systems are high-level languages, Ninja aims to be an assembler.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Build systems get slow when they need to make decisions.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] When you are in an edit-compile cycle you want it to be as fast as possible — you want the build system to do the minimum work necessary to figure out what needs to be built immediately.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Ninja contains the barest functionality necessary to describe arbitrary dependency graphs.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Its lack of syntax makes it impossible to express complex decisions.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Instead, Ninja is intended to be used with a separate program generating its input files.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] The generator program (like the `./configure` found in autotools projects) can analyze system dependencies and make as many decisions as possible up front so that incremental builds stay fast.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Going beyond autotools, even build-time decisions like "which compiler flags should I use?" or "should I build a debug or release-mode binary?" belong in the `.ninja` file generator.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] To restate, Ninja is faster than other build systems because it is painfully simple.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] You must tell Ninja exactly what to do when you create your project’s `.ninja` files.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Ninja is closest in spirit and functionality to Make, relying on simple dependencies between file timestamps.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] But fundamentally, make has a lot of *features*: suffix rules, functions, built-in rules that e.g. search for RCS files when building source.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Make’s language was designed to be written by humans.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Many projects find make alone adequate for their build problems.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] In contrast, Ninja has almost no features; just those necessary to get builds correct while punting most complexity to generation of the ninja input files.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Ninja by itself is unlikely to be useful for most projects.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Here are some of the features Ninja adds to Make.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Ninja currently works on Unix-like systems and Windows.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] It’s seen the most testing on Linux (and has the best performance there) but it runs fine on Mac OS X and FreeBSD.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] If your project is small, Ninja’s speed impact is likely unnoticeable.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] (However, even for small projects it sometimes turns out that Ninja’s limited syntax forces simpler build rules that result in faster builds.) Another way to say this is that if you’re happy with the edit-compile cycle time of your project already then Ninja won’t help.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] There are many other build systems that are more user-friendly or featureful than Ninja itself.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] For some recommendations: the Ninja author found the tup build system influential in Ninja’s design, and thinks redo's design is quite clever.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Ninja’s benefit comes from using it in conjunction with a smarter meta-build system.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] The meta-build system used to generate build files for Google Chrome and related projects (v8, node.js), as well as Google Fuchsia. gn can generate Ninja files for all platforms supported by Chrome.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] A widely used meta-build system that can generate Ninja files on Linux as of CMake version 2.8.8.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Newer versions of CMake support generating Ninja files on Windows and Mac OS X too.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] If you do this work, please let us know!
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] By default, it looks for a file named `build.ninja` in the current directory and builds all out-of-date targets.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] You can specify which targets (files) to build as command line arguments.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] There is also a special syntax `target^` for specifying a target as the first output of some rule containing the source you put in the command line, if one exists.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] For example, if you specify target as `foo.c^` then `foo.o` will get built (assuming you have those targets in your build files).
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Many of Ninja’s flags intentionally match those of Make; e.g `ninja -C build -j 20` changes into the `build` directory and runs 20 build commands in parallel.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Since version 1.13., Ninja builds can follow the GNU Make jobserver client protocol.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] This is useful when Ninja is invoked as part of a larger build system controlled by a top-level GNU Make instance, or any other jobserver pool implementation, as it allows better coordination between concurrent build tasks.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] In this case, Ninja will use the jobserver pool of job slots to control parallelism, instead of its default parallel implementation.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Note that load-average limitations (i.e. when using `-l<count>`) are still being enforced in this mode.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] On Posix, only the FIFO-based version of the protocol, which is implemented by GNU Make 4.4 and higher, is supported.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Ninja will detect when a pipe-based jobserver is being used (i.e. when `MAKEFLAGS` contains `--jobserver-auth=<read>,<write>`) and will print a warning, but will otherwise ignore it.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Ninja supports two environment variables to control its behavior: `NINJA_STATUS`, the progress status printed before the rule being run.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] The total number of edges that must be run to complete the build.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Remaining time (ETA) in [h:]mm:ss format.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] The percentage (in ppp% format) of time elapsed out of predicted total runtime.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] The default progress status is `"[%f/%t] "` (note the trailing space to separate from the build rule).
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Another example of possible progress status could be `"[%u/%r/%f] "`.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] If `MAKEFLAGS` is defined in the environment, if may alter how Ninja dispatches parallel build commands.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] See the GNU Jobserver support section for details.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] The `-t` flag on the Ninja command line runs some tools that we have found useful during Ninja’s development.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] The remainder of this manual is only useful if you are constructing Ninja files yourself: for example, if you’re writing a meta-build system or supporting a new language.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Ninja evaluates a graph of dependencies between files, and runs whichever commands are necessary to make your build target up to date as determined by file modification times.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] If you are familiar with Make, Ninja is very similar.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] A build file (default name: `build.ninja`) provides a list of *rules* — short names for longer commands, like how to run the compiler — along with a list of *build* statements saying how to build files using the rules — which rule to apply to which inputs to produce which outputs.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Conceptually, `build` statements describe the dependency graph of your project, while `rule` statements describe how to generate the files along a given edge of the graph.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Here’s a basic `.ninja` file that demonstrates most of the syntax.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] It will be used as an example for the following sections.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Despite the non-goal of being convenient to write by hand, to keep build files readable (debuggable), Ninja supports declaring shorter reusable names for strings.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Variables can also be referenced using curly braces like `${in}`.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Variables might better be called "bindings", in that a given variable cannot be changed, only shadowed.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] There is more on how shadowing works later in this document.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Rules declare a short name for a command line.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] They begin with a line consisting of the `rule` keyword and a name for the rule.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Then follows an indented set of `variable = value` lines.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] The basic example above declares a new rule named `cc`, along with the command to run.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] In the context of a rule, the `command` variable defines the command to run, `$in` expands to the list of input files (`foo.c`), and `$out` to the output files (`foo.o`) for the command.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] A full list of special variables is provided in the reference.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Build statements declare a relationship between input and output files.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] They begin with the `build` keyword, and have the format `build *outputs*: *rulename* *inputs*`.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Such a declaration says that all of the output files are derived from the input files.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] When the output files are missing or when the inputs change, Ninja will run the rule to regenerate the outputs.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] The basic example above describes how to build `foo.o`, using the `cc` rule.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] In the scope of a `build` block (including in the evaluation of its associated `rule`), the variable `$in` is the list of inputs and the variable `$out` is the list of outputs.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] A build statement may be followed by an indented set of `key = value` pairs, much like a rule.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] These variables will shadow any variables when evaluating the variables in the command.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] For more discussion of how scoping works, consult the reference.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] If you need more complicated information passed from the build statement to the rule (for example, if the rule needs "the file extension of the first input"), pass that through as an extra variable, like how `cflags` is passed above.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] If the top-level Ninja file is specified as an output of any build statement and it is out of date, Ninja will rebuild and reload it before building the targets requested by the user.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] `misc/ninja_syntax.py` in the Ninja distribution is a tiny Python module to facilitate generating Ninja files.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] It allows you to make Python calls like `ninja.rule(name='foo', command='bar', depfile='$out.d')` and it will generate the appropriate syntax.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Feel free to just inline it into your project’s build system if it’s useful.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] The special rule name `phony` can be used to create aliases for other targets.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] This makes `ninja foo` build the longer path.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Semantically, the `phony` rule is equivalent to a plain rule where the `command` does nothing, but phony rules are handled specially in that they aren’t printed when run, logged (see below), nor do they contribute to the command count printed as part of the build process.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] When a `phony` target is used as an input to another build rule, the other build rule will, semantically, consider the inputs of the `phony` rule as its own.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Therefore, `phony` rules can be used to group inputs, e.g. header files.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] `phony` can also be used to create dummy targets for files which may not exist at build time.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] If a phony build statement is written without any dependencies, the target will be considered out of date if it does not exist.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Without a phony build statement, Ninja will report an error if the file does not exist and is required by the build.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] By default, if no targets are specified on the command line, Ninja will build every output that is not named as an input elsewhere.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] You can override this behavior using a default target statement.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] A default target statement causes Ninja to build only a given subset of output files if none are specified on the command line.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Default target statements begin with the `default` keyword, and have the format `default *targets*`.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] A default target statement must appear after the build statement that declares the target as an output file.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] They are cumulative, so multiple statements may be used to extend the list of default targets.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] This causes Ninja to build the `foo`, `bar` and `baz` targets by default.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] For each built file, Ninja keeps a log of the command used to build it.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Using this log Ninja can know when an existing output was built with a different command line than the build files specify (i.e., the command line changed) and knows to rebuild the file.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] The log file is kept in the build root in a file called `.ninja_log`.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] If you provide a variable named `builddir` in the outermost scope, `.ninja_log` will be kept in that directory instead.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Ninja version labels follow the standard major.minor.patch format, where the major version is increased on backwards-incompatible syntax/behavioral changes and the minor version is increased on new behaviors.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Your `build.ninja` may declare a variable named `ninja_required_version` that asserts the minimum Ninja version required to use the generated file.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] declares that the build file relies on some feature that was introduced in Ninja 1.1 (perhaps the `pool` syntax), and that Ninja 1.1 or greater must be used to build.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Unlike other Ninja variables, this version requirement is checked immediately when the variable is encountered in parsing, so it’s best to put it at the top of the build file.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Ninja always warns if the major versions of Ninja and the `ninja_required_version` don’t match; a major version change hasn’t come up yet so it’s difficult to predict what behavior might be required.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] To get C/C++ header dependencies (or any other build dependency that works in a similar way) correct Ninja has some extra functionality.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] The problem with headers is that the full list of files that a given source file depends on can only be discovered by the compiler: different preprocessor defines and include paths cause different files to be used.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Some compilers can emit this information while building, and Ninja can use that to get its dependencies perfect.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Consider: if the file has never been compiled, it must be built anyway, generating the header dependencies as a side effect.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] If any file is later modified (even in a way that changes which headers it depends on) the modification will cause a rebuild as well, keeping the dependencies up to date.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] When loading these special dependencies, Ninja implicitly adds extra build edges such that it is not an error if the listed dependency is missing.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] This allows you to delete a header file and rebuild without the build aborting due to a missing input.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] `gcc` (and other compilers like `clang`) support emitting dependency information in the syntax of a Makefile.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] To bring this information into Ninja requires cooperation.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] On the Ninja side, the `depfile` attribute on the `build` must point to a path where this data is written.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] (Ninja only supports the limited subset of the Makefile syntax emitted by compilers.) Then the command must know to write dependencies into the `depfile` path.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] The `-MD` flag to `gcc` tells it to output header dependencies, and the `-MF` flag tells it where to write them.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] It turns out that for large projects (and particularly on Windows, where the file system is slow) loading these dependency files on startup is slow.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Ninja 1.3 can instead process dependencies just after they’re generated and save a compacted form of the same information in a Ninja-internal database.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Ninja supports this processing in two forms.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] `deps = msvc` specifies that the tool outputs header dependencies in the form produced by the Visual Studio compiler’s `/showIncludes` flag.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Briefly, this means the tool outputs specially-formatted lines to its stdout.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Ninja then filters these lines from the displayed output.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] No `depfile` attribute is necessary, but the localized string in front of the header file path should be globally defined.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] For instance, `msvc_deps_prefix = Note: including file:` for an English Visual Studio (the default).
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] If the include directory directives are using absolute paths, your depfile may result in a mixture of relative and absolute paths.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Paths used by other build rules need to match exactly.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Therefore, it is recommended to use relative paths in these cases.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Pools allow you to allocate one or more rules or edges a finite number of concurrent jobs which is more tightly restricted than the default parallelism.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] This can be useful, for example, to restrict a particular expensive rule (like link steps for huge executables), or to restrict particular build statements which you know perform poorly when run concurrently.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Each pool has a `depth` variable which is specified in the build file.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] The pool is then referred to with the `pool` variable on either a rule or a build statement.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] No matter what pools you specify, ninja will never run more concurrent jobs than the default parallelism, or the number of jobs specified on the command line (with `-j`).
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] There exists a pre-defined pool named `console` with a depth of 1.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] It has the special property that any task in the pool has direct access to the standard input, output and error streams provided to Ninja, which are normally connected to the user’s console (hence the name) but could be redirected.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] This can be useful for interactive tasks or long-running tasks which produce status updates on the console (such as test suites).
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] While a task in the `console` pool is running, Ninja’s regular output (such as progress status and output from concurrent tasks) is buffered until it completes.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] A build edge, which looks like `build *output1* *output2*: *rulename* *input1* *input2*`.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Implicit dependencies may be tacked on the end with `| *dependency1* *dependency2*`.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Order-only dependencies may be tacked on the end with `|| *dependency1* *dependency2*`.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] (See the reference on dependency types.) Validations may be tacked on the end with `|@ *validation1* *validation2*`.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] (See the reference on validations.) Implicit outputs *(available since Ninja 1.7)* may be added before the `:` with `| *output1* *output2*` and do not appear in `$out`.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Variable declarations, which look like `*variable* = *value*`.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Default target statements, which look like `default *target1* *target2*`.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] References to more files, which look like `subninja *path*` or `include *path*`.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] The difference between these is explained below in the discussion about scoping.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] A pool declaration, which looks like `pool *poolname*`.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Pools are explained in the section on pools.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Ninja is mostly encoding agnostic, as long as the bytes Ninja cares about (like slashes in paths) are ASCII.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] UTF-8 or ISO-8859-1 input files ought to work.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Comments begin with `#` and extend to the end of the line.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Statements like `build foo bar` are a set of space-separated tokens that end at the newline.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Newlines and spaces within a token must be escaped.
