[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Fundamentally, command lines behave differently on Unixes and Windows.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] On Unixes, commands are arrays of arguments.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] The Ninja `command` variable is passed directly to `sh -c`, which is then responsible for interpreting that string into an argv array.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Therefore, the quoting rules are those of the shell, and you can use all the normal shell operators, like `&&` to chain multiple commands, or `VAR=value cmd` to set environment variables.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] On Windows, commands are strings, so Ninja passes the `command` string directly to `CreateProcess`.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] (In the common case of simply executing a compiler this means there is less overhead.) Consequently, the quoting rules are determined by the called program, which on Windows are usually provided by the C library.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] If you need shell interpretation of the command (such as the use of `&&` to chain multiple commands), make the command execute the Windows shell by prefixing the command with `cmd /c`.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Ninja may error with "invalid parameter" which usually indicates that the command line length has been exceeded.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] There are two types of build outputs which are subtly different.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] *Implicit outputs*, as listed in a build line with the syntax `| *out1* *out2*` before the `:` of a build line *(available since Ninja 1.7)*.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] The semantics are identical to explicit outputs, the only difference is that implicit outputs don’t show up in the `$out` variable.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] This is for expressing outputs that don’t show up on the command line of the command.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] There are three types of build dependencies which are subtly different.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] *Implicit dependencies*, either as picked up from a `depfile` attribute on a rule or from the syntax `| *dep1* *dep2*` on the end of a build line.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] The semantics are identical to explicit dependencies, the only difference is that implicit dependencies don’t show up in the `$in` variable.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] *Order-only dependencies*, expressed with the syntax `|| *dep1* *dep2*` on the end of a build line.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] When these are out of date, the output is not rebuilt until they are built, but changes in order-only dependencies alone do not cause the output to be rebuilt.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Order-only dependencies can be useful for bootstrapping dependencies that are only discovered during build time: for example, to generate a header file before starting a subsequent compilation step.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] File paths are compared as is, which means that an absolute path and a relative path, pointing to the same file, are considered different by Ninja.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Validations listed on the build line cause the specified files to be added to the top level of the build graph (as if they were specified on the Ninja command line) whenever the build line is a transitive dependency of one of the targets specified on the command line or a default target.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Validations are added to the build graph regardless of whether the output files of the build statement are dirty are not, and the dirty state of the build statement that outputs the file being used as a validation has no effect on the dirty state of the build statement that requested it.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] A build edge can list another build edge as a validation even if the second edge depends on the first.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Validations are designed to handle rules that perform error checking but don’t produce any artifacts needed by the build, for example, static analysis tools.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Variables are expanded in paths (in a `build` or `default` statement) and on the right side of a `name = value` statement.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] When a `name = value` statement is evaluated, its right-hand side is expanded immediately (according to the below scoping rules), and from then on `$name` expands to the static string as the result of the expansion.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] It is never the case that you’ll need to "double-escape" a value to prevent it from getting expanded twice.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] All variables are expanded immediately as they’re encountered in parsing, with one important exception: variables in `rule` blocks are expanded when the rule is *used*, not when it is declared.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] In the following example, the `demo` rule prints "this is a demo of bar".
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Top-level variable declarations are scoped to the file they occur in.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Rule declarations are also scoped to the file they occur in.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] The `subninja` keyword, used to include another `.ninja` file, introduces a new scope.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] The included `subninja` file may use the variables and rules from the parent file, and shadow their values for the file’s scope, but it won’t affect values of the variables in the parent.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] To include another `.ninja` file in the current scope, much like a C `#include` statement, use `include` instead of `subninja`.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Variable declarations indented in a `build` block are scoped to the `build` block.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Build-level variables from the `build` block.
