[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Some use cases require implicit dependency information to be dynamically discovered from source file content *during the build* in order to build correctly on the first run (e.g.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] This is unlike header dependencies which are only needed on the second run and later to rebuild correctly.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] A build statement may have a `dyndep` binding naming one of its inputs to specify that dynamic dependency information must be loaded from the file.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] This specifies that file `foo` is a dyndep file.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Since it is an input, the build statement for `out` can never be executed before `foo` is built.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] As soon as `foo` is finished Ninja will read it to load dynamically discovered dependency information for `out`.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] This may include additional implicit inputs and/or outputs.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Ninja will update the build graph accordingly and the build will proceed as if the information was known originally.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] Files specified by `dyndep` bindings use the same lexical syntax as ninja build files and have the following layout.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] One or more build statements of the form: Every statement must specify exactly one explicit output and must use the rule name `dyndep`.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] The `| imp-outs...` and `| imp-ins...` portions are optional.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] build out | imp-outs... : dyndep | imp-ins...
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] An optional `restat` variable binding on each build statement.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] The build statements in a dyndep file must have a one-to-one correspondence to build statements in the ninja build file that name the dyndep file in a `dyndep` binding.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p01] No dyndep build statement may be omitted and no extra build statements may be specified.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p02] Consider a Fortran source file `foo.f90` that provides a module `foo.mod` (an implicit output of compilation) and another source file `bar.f90` that uses the module (an implicit input of compilation).
[src:ninja-build/manual-p02] This implicit dependency must be discovered before we compile either source in order to ensure that `bar.f90` never compiles before `foo.f90`, and that `bar.f90` recompiles when `foo.mod` changes.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p02] In this example the order-only dependencies ensure that `foobar.dd` is generated before either source compiles.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p02] Ninja will load this file to add `foo.mod` as an implicit output of `foo.o` and implicit input of `bar.o`.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p02] This ensures that the Fortran sources are always compiled in the proper order and recompiled when needed.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p02] Consider a tarball `foo.tar` that we want to extract.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p02] The extraction time can be recorded with a `foo.tar.stamp` file so that extraction repeats if the tarball changes, but we also would like to re-extract if any of the outputs is missing.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p02] However, the list of outputs depends on the content of the tarball and cannot be spelled out explicitly in the ninja build file.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p02] In this example the order-only dependency ensures that `foo.tar.dd` is built before the tarball extracts.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p02] Ninja will load this file to add `file1.txt` and `file2.txt` as implicit outputs of `foo.tar.stamp`, and to mark the build statement for `restat`.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p02] On future builds, if any implicit output is missing the tarball will be extracted again.
[src:ninja-build/manual-p02] The `restat` binding tells Ninja to tolerate the fact that the implicit outputs may not have modification times newer than the tarball itself (avoiding re-extraction on every build).
[src:ninja-build/ninja-build-org] Ninja is a small build system with a focus on speed.
[src:ninja-build/ninja-build-org] It differs from other build systems in two major respects: it is designed to have its input files generated by a higher-level build system, and it is designed to run builds as fast as possible.
[src:ninja-build/ninja-build-org] Where other build systems are high-level languages Ninja aims to be an assembler.
[src:ninja-build/ninja-build-org] Ninja build files are human-readable but not especially convenient to write by hand.
[src:ninja-build/ninja-build-org] (See the *generated* build file used to build Ninja itself.) These constrained build files allow Ninja to evaluate incremental builds quickly.
[src:ninja-build/ninja-build-org] Ninja's low-level approach makes it perfect for embedding into more featureful build systems; see a list of existing tools.
[src:ninja-build/ninja-build-org] Ninja is used to build Google Chrome, parts of Android, LLVM, and can be used in many other projects due to CMake's Ninja backend.
[src:ninja-build/ninja-build-org] See the manual for more: philosophical background, whether and how you can use Ninja for your project, platform support, and details about the language semantics.
[src:ninja-build/ninja-build-org] You can download the Ninja binary or find it in your system's package manager.
[src:ninja-build/ninja-build-system] In essence, Ninja is meant to replace Make, which is slow when performing incremental (or no-op) builds.
[src:ninja-build/ninja-build-system] This can considerably slow down developers working on large projects, such as Google Chrome, which compiles 40,000 input files into a single executable.
[src:ninja-build/ninja-build-system] In fact, Google Chrome is a main user and motivation for Ninja.
[src:ninja-build/ninja-build-system] It's also used to build Android (via Makefile translation by *Kati*), and is used by most developers working on LLVM.
[src:ninja-build/ninja-build-system] In contrast to Make, Ninja lacks features such as string manipulation, as Ninja build files are not meant to be written by hand.
[src:ninja-build/ninja-build-system] Instead, a "build generator" should be used to generate Ninja build files.
[src:ninja-build/ninja-build-system] Gyp, CMake, Meson, and gn are popular build management tools that support creating build files for Ninja.
[src:ninja-build/ninja-build-system] Below is an example of a Ninja build file that compiles two C source files (`source1.c` and `source2.c`) into object files and then links them into an executable called `myprogram`.
[src:ninja-build/software-build] A **software build** is the process of converting source code files into standalone software artifact(s) that can be run on a computer, or the result of doing so.
[src:ninja-build/software-build] In include functions such as version control, code quality analysis, compilation, and linking.
[src:ninja-build/software-build] In software production, builds optimize software for performance and distribution, packaging into formats such as '.*exe'; '.deb'; '.apk'*.
[src:ninja-build/software-build] The build process often employs specialized tools such as CMake, Make, or Gradle, and integrates with automation systems including Jenkins or GitHub Actions.
[src:ninja-build/software-build] Despite advancements, challenges such as dependency conflicts, platform compatibility, and long compile times, remain problems.
[src:ninja-build/software-build] In software development, building software is an end-to-end process that involves many distinct functions.
[src:ninja-build/software-build] Some of these functions are described below.
[src:ninja-build/software-build] The version control function carries out activities such as workspace creation and updating, baselining and reporting.
[src:ninja-build/software-build] It creates an environment for the build process to run in and captures metadata about the inputs and output of the build process to ensure repeatability and reliability.
[src:ninja-build/software-build] Tools such as Git, AccuRev or StarTeam help with these tasks by offering tools to tag specific points in history as being important, and more.
[src:ninja-build/software-build] Also known as static program analysis/static code analysis this function is responsible for checking that developers have adhered to the seven axes of code quality: comments, unit tests, duplication, complexity, coding rules, potential bugs and architecture & design.
[src:ninja-build/software-build] Ensuring a project has high-quality code results in fewer bugs and influences nonfunctional requirements such as maintainability, extensibility and readability; which have a direct impact on the ROI for a business.
[src:ninja-build/software-build] This is only a small feature of managing the build process.
[src:ninja-build/software-build] The compilation function turns source files into directly executable or intermediate objects.
[src:ninja-build/software-build] Not every project will require this function.
[src:ninja-build/software-build] While for simple programs the process consists of a single file being compiled, for complex software the source code may consist of many files and may be combined in different ways to produce many different versions.
[src:ninja-build/software-build] A linker or link editor is a computer program that combines intermediate software build files such as object and library files into a single executable file such as a program or library.
[src:ninja-build/software-build] A linker is often part of a toolchain that includes a compiler and/or assembler that generates intermediate files that the linker processes.
[src:ninja-build/software-build] The linker may be integrated with other toolchain tools such that the user does not interact with the linker directly.
[src:ninja-build/software-build] A simpler version that writes its output directly to memory is called the *loader*, though loading is typically considered a separate process.
[src:ninja-build/software-build] The process of building a computer program is usually managed by a build tool, a program that coordinates and controls other programs.
[src:ninja-build/software-build] Examples of such a program are make, Gradle, Ant, Maven, Rake, SCons and Phing.
[src:ninja-build/software-build] The build utility typically needs to compile the various files, in the correct order.
[src:ninja-build/software-build] If the source code in a particular file has not changed then it may not need to be recompiled ("may not" rather than "need not" because it may itself depend on other files that have changed).
[src:ninja-build/software-build] Sophisticated build utilities and linkers attempt to refrain from recompiling code that does not need it, to shorten the time required to complete the build.
[src:ninja-build/software-build] A more complex process may involve other programs producing code or data as part of the build process and software.
